This paper deals with the problem of estimating an unknown subspace from partially observed vectors, which is a common problem in signal processing and machine learning. The paper uses tools from information theory, linear algebra, and optimization, which are all relevant to the subfield of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the bias of a certain estimator, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper involves analyzing large deviation results, which is a topic in probability theory and statistics, and is relevant to the subfield of data science (cs.DS). The paper also discusses optimization programs and perturbation bounds, which are topics in numerical analysis and optimization, and are relevant to the subfields of scientific computing (cs.SI) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). Overall, the paper is likely to be classified under cs.IT, cs.LG, cs.DS, cs.SI, and cs.NA, in that order of likelihood.
